## Introduction {#introduction}

The purpose of this report is to conduct a usability test of the Teriyaki & Wok website. This test will consist of three separate tasks, each assigned to a different user. Users will be administered a pre-test to assess their baseline computer proficiency, experience using the website or similar websites, and basic demographic information, including age, gender, and educational background. A post-test will be administered after completion of the tasks to assess any issues when interacting with the website. Results from the post-test will be used to make recommendations to the website designer to address current issues and inform future improvements.

## Test Methods {#test-methods}

To prepare for the testing, a suitable test audience was needed to gather proper data on the user experience. Using the guidelines outlined in the “Guerrilla Testing with Usability Cafe” by Google for Developers, an in-person test was conducted with three users who had not previously used the website. Users completed a pre-test questionnaire and were then given a specific task to complete on the website (i.e., completing an order). Users were asked to communicate their thoughts out loud during the testing process, with no input being made by the test administrator. The time to complete each task was recorded for further evaluation purposes.

To determine which tasks the participants would be asked to complete, a screening of the website was performed to identify the key features. This screening identified the following three features: 

1) ordering online  
2) signing up for loyalty rewards,   
3) and purchasing a gift card

These were identified by their presence on the website, including but not limited to: action buttons related to these features, advertising, and wording that included these terms. To protect participants' online identity, a proxy email address and phone were provided for the user before the start of testing to be used for loyalty sign-ups. All charges were made on the same card in another effort to protect participants. Participants were offered free food as their incentive for completing their task.

Based on the information gathered before testing, participants were asked to complete these three tasks:

1. Complete an online order. Please select more than one item to order. Request a modification to any/all of the items in your order, as desired. This can include substituting a side dish (e.g., substituting vegetables for rice) or special requests (e.g., cooking the beef medium-well).  
2. Purchase a gift card and load it with $20.  
3. Sign up for the loyalty rewards using the email and phone number given to you at the start of this test.

	  
After completing the task, users were asked to complete a post-test questionnaire regarding their experience. The post-test questionnaire consisted of open-ended (e.g., how was your experience) and closed questions (e.g., were you able to complete the task). Both questionnaires are attached in the appendix of this report.

## Findings {#findings}

### **Task 1:** **Complete an online order with more than one item. Please request modifications to any/all of the items.** {#task-1:-complete-an-online-order-with-more-than-one-item.-please-request-modifications-to-any/all-of-the-items.}

All users were able to complete the task in the given time frame of five minutes, with the average time being 4’30”. All users clicked on the first available ‘order online’ button and experienced a moment of confusion when taken to the online ordering page. Since users have previously ordered food online, they noted that this step of the process was not unfamiliar to small businesses, but still gave them hesitation. All users noted the lack of pictures on the menu.

* Blake had the most experience with ordering food online and was confident when presented with the task. She navigated between the ordering page from the home page and took some time to select an item to add to the cart. She was able to substitute a side for her dish successfully.  
* Claire had difficulty with the online ordering page, navigating back several times and clicking on the second online ordering button in hopes that it would lead to a more formal-looking page. After testing both pages, she proceeded with the first option to complete her order. She was able to modify her meal after spending a significant amount of time reading the options to understand what was standard for the dish she had chosen.  
* Michael had the second most experience ordering food online. Similar to the others, he was confused with the web page and inquired about the option to call in the order. This came up again when modifying the dishes. In the post-test, Michael identified the lack of pictures and clarity in modifications as the most difficult part.

### Task 2: Purchase a gift card. {#task-2:-purchase-a-gift-card.}

No users were able to complete this task due to a broken link within the website. The button for “purchase a gift card” failed to open the corresponding web page, leaving users on the home screen with no error message or feedback. This led to each user giving up and using the full amount of allotted time.

### Task 3: Sign up for the loyalty program. {#task-3:-sign-up-for-the-loyalty-program.}

Users all experienced an issue when signing up for the loyalty program, noting in the post-test that they expected to be led to a different web page. Instead, the loyalty rewards are linked to the online ordering page, and users must navigate that page to sign up for the loyalty program.

* Blake commented on the difficulty of signing up for the loyalty program. In the post-test screen, she commented that there should be a pop-up or other message that lets the user know they have successfully signed up, or incentives should be offered to those who sign up.  
* Claire had difficulty finding the button for signing up for loyalty rewards on the ordering screen, again navigating back to the home page to retrace her steps.  
* Michael shared a similar experience to Claire, feeling confused when brought to the online ordering screen as opposed to a dedicated loyalty sign-up. This was noted in the post-test results as well, stating that loyalty rewards should be made clearer.


## Recommendation {#recommendation}

Based on the findings from user testing, the website should first address the issue of purchasing gift cards and fix the link so that customers may purchase gift cards online. Second, they should invest resources in creating system visibility and feedback for their website so users are informed of their decisions and face less confusion. An effort for more visual cohesion should also be made, specifically with the disparity between the home page and the online ordering and loyalty pages. All users noted that menu pictures would be a great addition, as well.

## Conclusion {#conclusion}

Ultimately, the Teriyaki & Wok website serves its purpose by allowing users to order food online, but it can be improved significantly by supporting gift card purchases and updating the visual interface. By clarifying menu options and loyalty rewards, the usability of the website can be greatly improved and help promote overall sales.
